WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello everyone. Welcome. My name is Jeroen Janssens and today I'm going to talk about how you can combine R and Python.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.840
In order to get the job done, you need to, you know, resort to other languages, however

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:42.840
strange they may be. And the same is for data science, right? There might be situations

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:50.360
where you need to make combinations of tools or languages out there. So, for example, you

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:55.439
may have written a Python application that needs to use an algorithm that's only available

00:00:55.480 --> 00:01:01.279
inside an R package. Or maybe you've done your analysis in R which needs to be part

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:08.279
of a larger ETL pipeline written in Python. So, what do you do in those situations? Well,

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:14.800
you take a polyglot approach. So, I've had a few of those situations over the past few

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:20.680
years and I want to share some stories with you today. Now, this won't be a very technical

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:26.120
talk, because I think the main challenge is not going to be the code that you need to

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:33.120
write, but your mindset. The way you're going to handle this. Your way of thinking. I really

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:41.199
believe that if you want to be effective as a data scientist, you need to be able to recognize

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:48.199
when it's okay to use the same language for the entire project or when it's better to

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:55.360
get in the help of some other tool or language. So, who here uses R or Python? Show of hands.

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:04.879
R or Python? Not that many. R or Python? All right. That's okay. If you're watching this

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.919
on YouTube, almost everybody raised their hands. Keep your hands raised. Who here is

00:02:16.919 --> 00:02:23.919
using SQL? Congratulations. You are already a polyglot data scientist. Perhaps without

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:30.919
even being aware of this. So, there are, of course, many other languages and tools available,

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:38.240
but in this talk, I'm going to focus on just R and Python. And rest assured, I'm not suggesting

00:02:38.399 --> 00:02:44.360
that you should transition from R to Python. Although I realize, I've heard that, you know,

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:49.559
there are plenty of people in a situation at the place that they work that they do need

00:02:49.559 --> 00:02:56.279
to transition. But I really see this as a spectrum. Right? It's not R or Python. You

00:02:56.279 --> 00:03:02.000
can combine these two beautiful languages in multiple ways. And which one is best depends

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:09.000
entirely on your situation. Okay. Story time. About 13 years ago, I started working as a

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:16.639
data scientist at a startup in New York City. I was the first data scientist, and all the

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:24.240
engineers there were using Python. So, I'm like, all right. I got this. We've got pandas.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:29.639
We've got notebooks. Oh, my. I don't want to visualize my data using Matplotlib. I had

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:36.639
seen what ggplot2 could do. So, what did I do? I took a polyglot approach. So, the solution

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:44.440
conceptually looks like this. Right? And try to think if you have had a similar situation

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:50.000
in the past that you where this might have been appropriate or maybe there is something

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.000
currently going on. I don't know. But in my specific situation, I there was some IPython

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:02.639
magic that I could use that uses the package rpy2 under the hood. So, if you're in a similar

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:09.639
situation, then I could recommend rpy2. Now, in this particular case, it was fine because

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:17.239
I was the only data scientist doing this. Yeah? And for data visualization specifically,

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:22.279
as we have seen in the previous presentation as well, there is now the wonderful plot9

00:04:22.279 --> 00:04:29.279
package, a Python port of ggplot2. And speaking of which, Posit is currently organizing a

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:34.600
contest for plot9 as well as a table contest. So, if you're into, you know, visualizing

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:41.359
data or creating tables, I recommend that you participate. So, it could be a nice excuse

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:47.880
to try out that other language. So, the deadline is October 3rd for these two contests. And

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:53.519
if you search for 2025 plot9 contest, then you'll get to see the announcement and you

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:56.519
can see more details.

00:04:56.519 --> 00:05:03.519
All right. Story time. I was working at a Dutch telecommunications company in the Netherlands

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:14.519
at a team that only used R. All right. Fantastic. I used the tidyverse and ggplot2 still and

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:22.600
I did some fancy dimensionality reduction and I created, you know, a machine learning

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:27.880
model. I was asked to create a machine learning model that would then be used on their website.

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:34.200
Yeah. So, I had this nicely wrapped up and it was all good to go. So, when I then spoke

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:40.880
to the team responsible for serving these models, right, would be an API kind of situation,

00:05:41.559 --> 00:05:48.559
they were like, yeah, we don't do that here. We only use Python. So, luckily, I used annoy,

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:56.440
which is a C++ library for doing approximate nearest neighbor search. So, I realize that's

00:05:56.440 --> 00:06:03.239
really specific. But this particular package had both language bindings in R and Python

00:06:03.239 --> 00:06:08.640
available. So, what I could do is what I like to call the save and load approach. It doesn't

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:15.000
have to be that complicated. You can save intermediate results, right, say to disk or

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:22.000
to a database and let some other process read this. Right? It doesn't have to be fancy.

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:29.160
This might work. And it also doesn't have to be, you know, in our situation we had multiple

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:36.000
processes reading from this database. But, you know, it could be a single one and those

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:41.959
languages could be flipped. So, this approach is very flexible. But keep in mind that you

00:06:41.959 --> 00:06:48.959
may need additional coordination, right, so that you ensure that both sides of the database

00:06:48.959 --> 00:06:55.959
or disk are being run at the correct times. So, the polyglot approach is nothing new.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:05.480
Yeah? So, the ability to easily combine multiple tools and languages has been around for over

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:12.480
50 years. 50 years. When the Unix command line got its pipe operator. So, this is not

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:22.480
so much a single story. But over the past 15 years, this has become more a way of working

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:29.600
for me. And the idea here is that the pipe operator connects the standard output stream

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:37.359
of the first tool to the standard input stream of the second tool. Right? There's no saving

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:43.720
to disk. Now, keep in mind that according to the Unix philosophy, text is the universal

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:50.040
interface. So, if you have to write and read, you know, a data frame, that will most likely

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:57.040
be CSV. And so that's something to keep in mind. Now, you can send binary data over the

00:07:57.679 --> 00:08:02.480
pipe, but then you wouldn't be playing nice with the gazillion other tools out there.

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:08.200
And again, this approach works for any language. Yeah? And you can make that chain as long

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:13.519
as you want. But hey, it's not for everybody. I realize that. But if you do want to give

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:20.519
this a go, I can you might enjoy this book I wrote a couple of years ago. It's available

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:27.559
for free online. Now, the last story that I want to share with

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:35.039
you is more a cautionary tale. So, I was once again working at a Dutch company. This time

00:08:35.479 --> 00:08:42.479
a utilities company. And they had a huge ETL pipeline, so to speak, set up. It started

00:08:43.479 --> 00:08:50.479
off as some R code, and then later on they added some Python and some copying and RPy2.

00:08:53.359 --> 00:09:00.359
But eventually it became a process that took over 700 gigabytes of RAM on a single machine

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:09.280
to run. I believe it took over two days to finish. And that was okay, because these calculations

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:16.280
only needed to be done twice a year. They were needed to make predictions about the

00:09:18.359 --> 00:09:25.359
utility grid and how much power was going over them so that they could make choices

00:09:26.719 --> 00:09:33.719
on where to reinforce the network, add additional transformers. So, pretty important stuff.

00:09:34.239 --> 00:09:40.679
But then management came down to us and they said, all right, so instead of doing this

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:45.719
for 10% of our network, why don't you do this for everything that we have? And instead

00:09:45.719 --> 00:09:50.599
of doing this twice a year, why don't you do this every week? Oh, yeah, your budget

00:09:50.599 --> 00:09:57.599
is 5,000 euros a month. So, we had a real problem here. We had the reverse problem,

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:05.159
because using both Python and R was really hurting our performance. It also made our

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:12.640
virtual machines, our Docker images way too large and it was very difficult to maintain.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:19.640
So, we needed to convince the rest of the team that we actually needed a monoglot approach.

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:27.640
So, we were successful in the end. We suggested, okay, let's use Polars. Mind you, this is

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:35.840
almost three years ago, before Polars was cool. But we were really excited. I mean,

00:10:36.679 --> 00:10:40.919
in the end, it was a big success. Everything was rewritten to Python and Polars and it

00:10:40.919 --> 00:10:47.919
all worked out. But it was a big investment. So, my colleague and I, we learned so much

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:53.359
about Polars. We were so excited about it that we decided to write a book about this

00:10:53.359 --> 00:10:57.919
at the same time. Now, on this website, you can find more information and get the first

00:10:57.919 --> 00:11:04.919
chapter for free. Right? And for five bucks, I can send you the PDF. All right. So, now,

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:15.159
so just to keep in mind that everything that you add, every dependency, and, yeah, also

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:22.159
for packages and tools for entire languages, everything that you add, of course, adds complexity

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:29.159
to this. Yeah? And space. Not only in memory, but also on disk. Right? Adds time. It's

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:37.880
usually not, depending on what you want to do, it usually takes longer if you want to

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:41.640
combine languages. Unless you decide, all right, we've got to rewrite this part in

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:48.640
Fortran, but that's another talk. Yeah? And, of course, risk. So, I hear some of you thinking,

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:55.799
what about Python within R? Yeah? And I have to be honest here. I haven't had a situation

00:11:55.799 --> 00:12:01.119
yet where I needed to do this. But if you do, then I can definitely recommend that you

00:12:01.119 --> 00:12:08.119
check out Reticulate and Arrow. Right? Reticulate for running Python code in R and Arrow for

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:16.000
zero copy data sharing. Yeah? And I also want to give a shout out to Positron

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:23.400
and Quarto. Two tools that make it particularly convenient and pleasant to work with these

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:30.400
two languages. Positron as an IDE and Quarto as a format. So, I hope that through these

00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:36.880
stories I've been able to convince you that there are definitely situations where it's

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:43.880
worthwhile to embrace a polyglot approach. Yeah? You know, it takes time and skill to

00:12:47.599 --> 00:12:52.799
sort of recognize when this is appropriate and which approach is the right one, which

00:12:52.799 --> 00:12:59.799
tools should I use. But I shouldn't stop you from, you know, clinging on to doing everything

00:13:00.799 --> 00:13:07.799
in the same language. How beautiful that language may be. Like Dutch.

00:13:07.799 --> 00:13:14.799
So, all right. So, yeah. I've shared with you through my stories a couple of these approaches

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:23.280
and tools, Rpy2, Reticulate, Arrow, saving and loading. Right? So, whatever you do, be

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:31.280
mindful of the complexity that you're adding. Space, time, risk. Right? It may be more pragmatic.

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:38.880
It may get the job done. But, yeah, I think if you take all that into account, then you'll

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:45.880
be good. Thank you very much.

00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:53.880
Okay. We have a few minutes. So, send your questions in. Let's see. One, managing versions

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:04.640
in each language takes work. Is it twice as bad or more when using both?

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:11.520
It's more than twice as bad. Yeah. Well, I mean, it depends on how coupled the two processes

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:18.039
will be. Right? If you're using Reticulate and Rpy2, there's a really tight connection

00:14:18.039 --> 00:14:24.440
between the two. Again, if you're using the other two approaches, like using piping or

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:30.520
the save and load approach, right, where you have, say, a hard disk or a database in between,

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:34.760
you decouple that and it's exactly twice as bad.

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:40.719
Okay. Another question. Could you explain a little bit more about how rewriting your

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:46.320
R plus Python code with Polars helps speed things up? Could you have used Arrow?

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:53.320
Yeah. So, Polars uses Arrow and then some changes. But, yeah, it uses an in-columnar

00:14:53.960 --> 00:15:00.960
or an in-memory columnar data frame format. So, yeah. Yeah. Arrow. Good stuff. Parquet.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:06.760
Right? These kind of things. Okay. How do you determine when it's worth exploring

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:11.880
doing something in another language if you can already do it in your primary language?

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:18.880
Yeah. So, I think you'll recognize when there's a problem. Right? You shouldn't just add another

00:15:22.239 --> 00:15:29.080
language just for the sake of it. But if you're like, maybe you work at a consultancy firm

00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:33.000
and you're asked to do something now in a different language and you're like, oh, man,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.599
I wish I just had that algorithm that I use in that other language. Then, of course, then

00:15:37.599 --> 00:15:41.880
you're feeling it. Then you're feeling, okay, there is now a situation. Wait a minute. I

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:47.440
remember what this Dutch guy was saying. I should use a polyglot approach. So, but if

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:54.440
there is no problem, then I don't see any reason why you should not stick to the same

00:15:55.400 --> 00:16:01.719
language. Okay. One more. What is something that R is missing for Python and something

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:08.760
Python is missing from R? Well, as we've seen in the previous talk, I mean, there are, the

00:16:11.559 --> 00:16:18.559
two languages are, there are quite some fundamental differences between the two. Right? With R,

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:24.039
you've all been spoiled with the tidyverse and non-standard evaluation and the pipe operator.

00:16:24.039 --> 00:16:31.039
Right? Those are things that aren't easily done in Python. So, yeah. I mean, I think

00:16:31.719 --> 00:16:38.719
that's about it. I was really hoping for an applause there. I don't know. But the tidyverse.

